Fifth Avenue, west side, at W. 54th Street, showing St. Lukes Hospital at the N. W. corner of same. This structure was erected in 1858, thru the efforts of the Rev. Dr. William A. Muhlenberg, the rector of the Church of the Holy Communion. He began this work in 1846 and in 1850 raised a subscription of $100,000. A corporation was formed and in 1854 opened an infirmary in a Sixth Avenue house to be conducted by the Sisters of the Holy Communion. In 1888 a Training School for Nurses was established. In 1892, the Trustees purchased a tract on W. 113th Street, near the (then) proposed Cathedral of St. John and erected a new hospital. This site in 1939 is occupied by the 9 story University Club.

This view shows, a vacant lot at the S. W. corner of this point, at the left of which stood for years the Rockefeller residence. See views on 54th Street for same.

About 1859

gift of George T. Bagoe

54th Street, west from and including Fifth Avenue, showing St. Luke's Hospital, opened in 1859, on the north side of 54th Street. Its front yard, at the N.W. corner of Fifth Avenue, is the future site of the University Club. 4 East 54th Street, the four-story house, has been built since 1862. The view is not quite inclusive enough to be sure, but work can hardly have more than begun on St. Thomas Protestant Episcopal Church on the N.W. corner of Fifth Avenue and 53rd Street.
About 1865.

from the original by J. H. Beal.

4 West 54th Street, south side, west of Fifth Avenue (left) showing the Rockeffer home at a time when it was the property of William P. Williams and who had completed same in the year previous. The emtpy area to the south is the property of Columbia University. They succeeded Dr. David Hosack (Botanic Gardens) in ownership in 1814. The latter had purchased it from the City for $4,807.36 in 1811. These 12 acres comprise the present Rockefeller Center.

Note the absence of lamp lights and buildings at the left. St. Patricks Cathedral is shown there, under construction.

This photograph is taken from St. Lukes Hospital which is on the opposite, or north side of 54th Street. Not the gate and entrance of same in the foreground.

1866

(Positive)

Fifth Avenue, west side, north from West 54th Street, showing prominently Dr. Hall's Fifth Avenue Presbyterian Church at the N. W. corner of 55th Street. Organized in 1808, their first church was erected on Cedar Street. The Rev. John Brodhead Romeyn became the first pastor, retaining his connection with the parish until his death in 1825. In common with all the earlier churches, the Cedar Street parish made several removals farther uptown; in 1834 to Duane Street; in 1852 to its first Fifth Avenue church, at the corner of 19th Street, when the corporate name was changed, and again, in 1875 to the present location. To the left is St. Lukes Hospital, occupying the Avenue frontage from 54th to 55th Street's.
About 1885
Thru New York Historical Society

Fifth Avenue, at the N.W. corner of West 54th Street, showing St. Luke's Hospital, erected in 1858. Beginning in 1846 under the guidance of the Rev. Dr. Wm. A. Muhlenberg, rector of the Church of the Holy Communion, a public appeal for funds in 1850 resulted in the formation of a corporation and in subscriptions amounting to S100,000. An infirmary was opened on Sixth Avenue in 1854. This work was transferred to the newly erected hospital in
1858.
Increased demands necessitated the abandonment of this structure and the erection of a new building on 113th Street, near the Cathedral of St. John. The corner stone there was laid, May 6, 1893. For further details of this humanitarian work see pages 471-3 of
Kings Handbook of New York, 1893.
1894
Urbrock Collection
H. W. Tiemmann Company, photo
Fifth Avenue, west side, from West 54th to 55th streets, showing St. Luke's Hospital. The main entrance is on the left, 54th Street. Organized in 1850, the Sisters oi the Holy Communion opened an infirmary on Sixth Avenue in 1854. Upon completion of the building shown in 1858 their work was transferred here. In connection with the hospital, s training. school for nurses was established in 1888. The cornerstone of their new hospital on Morningside Heights
(at West 113th Street) was laid May 6, 1893.
Note at the right margin the partial glimpse of Dr. Tall's Ninth Avenue Presbyterian Church at the N. W. corner of
West 55th Street and the Avenue.

18 to 4 West 54th Street, south side, east from but not including Sixth, to but not including Fifth Aves., showing the 9-story (No. 10) and contiguous to it eastward, the 4-story (No. 4), Rockefeller residences. These two houses are to be demolished and the land will be used by the Museum of Modern Art as a garden for the display of sculpture. It was presented to the Museum by Mr. and Mrs. John D. Rockefeller Jr. as a gift, shortly after the demise of the elder Rockefeller. No. 4, the 4-story residence which stands within an enclosed garden, was the residence of John D. Rockefeller Sr. It was built in 1865 and was bought by Mr. Rockefeller in 1895. The 9-story house, No. 10, is the residence of John D. Rockefeller Jr. and is one of the largest private homes in the city. It was built in 1912 at a cost of 200,000 dollars. (For further information see the New York Times of June 18, 1937, page 1).

December 28, 1936.

P. L. Sperr.

10 to 22 West 54th Street, south side, between Fifth and Sixth Aves,, as viewed eastward, showing the lower portions of structures under demolition for the new Museum of Modern Art. On the left is the home of John D. Rockefeller (No. 10) which is to be included.

October 1937.

R.W. Hill.

(1) West 54th Street, west from Fifth Ave. On the left are the two Rockefeller homes; that of the late John D. Sr. being the first. A more elaborate and costly structure is adjacent to same and is known as the John D. Jr. residence. This property, recently bequeathed to the Museum of Modern Art will be utilized by the recipients for a new and larger Museum than their former home on 53rd Street.

54th Street, west from Fifth Avenue. To the right is the University Club at the N.W. corner of this point, while beyond is the Warwick, at the N..E. corner of Sixth Avenue. Between same is a modern structure, reputed to have been financed by the Rockefeller who formerly resided opposite same. At this date, the John D. Rockefeller Sr. home is gone leaving his son 's standing (left center), That will soon follow as per
article in the New York Sun of Sept. 12, 1938.
Views 2 and 3 are eastward from Sixth Avenue and are progressive. Note in the last the fenced clearance where the gardens of the new Museum of Modern Art are to be. These will eventually include the Rockefeller buildings sites.

4 West 54th Street, adjoining the S.W. corner of Fifth Avenue, showing the John D. Rockefeller Sr. home and garage as viewed eastward towards the Avenue. According to the New York Times of May 16, 1938 the 80 year old house will be demolished, leaving the garage. At that time no plans were announced for the improvement of this site. Latter it became known that a garden for the new Museum of Modern Art
will be here and include the John D. Jr. home site.
May 3, 1938.
View 2: June 20, 1938.
P. L. Sper

25 to 33 W. 54th Street, north side, between Fifth and Sixth Avenues, showing amongst same, No. 27 which was the town house of Chauncey M. Depew for many years. According to the New York Sun of April 29, 1938 this has been sold to the N.K. Winston interests, who have acquired same in connection with plans for a 14 story apartment house. The Wallenstein Construction Co. is associated with this organization in this project. Yale University, Elise Strang L'Esperance, May Strang, Charles A. Paulding and Anne Depew Paulding were the sellers.

P. L. Sperr

May 3, 1938.

West 54th Street, south side, between Fifth and Sixth Avenues, showing a clearance to the west of the Rockefeller homes. This extends thru to 53rd Street and includes the building that formerly housed the Museum of Modern Art. Upon this site a new structure and garden for this institution will rise. Several newspaper accounts refer to this demolition, one of which appeared in the New York Times of May 16, 1938. In the background are units of Rockefeller Center, same being the 45 story International Bldg. and the 70 story R.C.A. Bldg. The photographer is viewing southward from No. 17 (in No. 1) and No. 25 (in No. 2) W. 54th Street.

May 3, 1938.
Views 1 and 2

P. L. Sperr

W. 54th Street, south side, west of Fifth Avenue, showing the demolition of the Rockefeller home. This is to provide a grace for a garden at the rear of the Museum of Modern Art.
